'''Girolamo Sernigi''' (1453- after 1510<ref name=rav>{{citation |title=A Journal of the First Voyage of Vasco Da Gama, 1497-1499 |year=1898 |editor-first=Ernest George |editor-last=Ravenstein |editor-link=Ernest George Ravenstein |publisher= Hakluyt Society |url=https://archive.org/download/ajournalfirstvo01ravegoog |pages=119–120}}</ref>) was an Italian merchant, originally from [[Republic of Florence|Florence]], based in [[Lisbon]], Portugal. Circa 1500, Florentine merchants were the most prominent foreign group active in Lisbon's economic life and played an important role in the financing of Portuguese maritime expeditions in search of new products and markets.{{sfn|Lach|1994|p=103-104}} Sernigi himself was a part owner of one of the ships of [[Pedro Álvares Cabral]]'s [[2nd Portuguese India Armada (Cabral, 1500)|fleet]],{{sfn|Lach|1994|p=103-104}} and was in contact with members of the first Portuguese expeditions sailing to India around the [[Cape of Good Hope]], such as [[Gonçalo Coelho]] and [[Gaspar da Gama]].
Sernigi is remembered today as the author of letters in which he reported news of the overseas exploration to his relatives and associates back in Florence, and which became some of the most detailed accounts of the Portuguese expeditions of the period. <ref>{{citation |first=Donald Frederick |last=Lach |publisher=University of Chicago Press |year=1994 |isbn=0-226-46731-7 |title=Asia in the Making of Europe: The Century of Discovery : Book One |volume=Volume 1, Book 1: the Century of Discovery |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=xD52ge5a8vYC&pg=PA155 |pages=155–157 }}</ref>
In 1510, he personally commanded a ship going to [[Malacca]].<ref name=rav/>
== Notes == {{reflist}}
