on|Morrison]]''')|marksize=6}} }} {{location map+|United Kingdom |float=left |width=400 |caption=Birthplaces of British-born Australian Prime Ministers |places= {{Location map~|United Kingdom|position=right|lat=55.83461|long=-4.50272|label='''[[George Reid (Australian politician)|Reid]]'''|marksize=6}} {{Location map~|United Kingdom|position=right|lat=55.612222|long=-4.552778|label='''[[Andrew Fisher|Fisher]]'''|marksize=6}} {{Location map~|United Kingdom|position=right|lat=53.0159|long=-2.2675|label='''[[Joseph Cook|Cook]]'''|marksize=6}} {{Location map~|United Kingdom|position=left|lat=51.4887|long=-0.1395|label='''[[Billy Hughes|Hughes]]'''|marksize=6}} {{Location map~|United Kingdom|position=right|lat=51.405|long=-3.27|label='''[[Julia Gillard|Gillard]]'''|marksize=6}} {{Location map~|United Kingdom|position=right|lat=51.507222|long=-0.1275|label='''[[Tony Abbott|Abbott]]'''|marksize=6}} }} As of {{Monthyear}}, five of the six states claim the distinction of being the birthplace of a prime minister. Twelve prime ministers, those born prior to the [[federation of Australia]], were born in [[Colonies of Australia|British colonies within Australia]], rather than independent Australian states. The birthplaces of eight prime ministers are within sovereign states that are separate from Australia, including six in [[Great Britain]], one in New Zealand and [[Chris Watson|one]] in [[Chile]].
The number of prime ministers born per state are: * One: South Australia and Tasmania. * Three: Queensland. * Eight: New South Wales. * Eight: Victoria.
'''States and territories that have not born a prime minister:''' Australian Capital Territory, Northern Territory, Western Australia.
