{{about|the geographical plain between Greece and the Republic of Macedonia|the political unit in Macedonia|Pelagonia Statistical Region}} [[Image:PaeoniaPaioniaMap.png|thumb|right|250px|Location of Pelagonia]] [[File:Pelagonija.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Pelagonia seen from [[Baba Mountain, Macedonia|Baba Mountain]]]] '''Pelagonia''' ([[Ancient Greek|Greek]]: Πελαγονíα, ''Pelagonía''; [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]]: Пелагонија, ''Pelagonija'') is a geographical region of [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]].
==History== [[File:Macedonian Kingdom.jpg|thumb|right|350px|Map of the Kingdom of Macedon with Pelagonia located in the northwest districts of the kingdom.]]
In antiquity, ancient Pelagonia was roughly bounded by [[Paionia]] to the north and east, [[Lynkestis]] and [[Almopia]] to the south and [[Illyria]] to the west; and was inhabited by the Pelagones, an [[Ancient Greece|ancient Greek]] tribe of [[Upper Macedonia]], who were centered at the Pelagonian [[plain]] and, according to [[Hecataeus of Miletus|Hecataeus]] (1 FGrH 107) and [[Strabo]],<ref>Strabo 9.5: For in consequence of the renown and ascendency of the Thessalians and Macedonians, those Epeirote, who bordered nearest upon them, became, some voluntarily, others by force, incorporated among the Macedonians and Thessalians. In this manner the Athamanes, Aethices, and Talares were joined to the Thessalians, and the Orestae, Pelagones, and Elimiotae to the Macedonians.</ref> were an Epirote [[Molossian]] tribe.<ref>John Boardman and N. G. L. Hammond. ''The Cambridge Ancient History Volume 3, Part 3: The Expansion of the Greek World, Eighth to Sixth Centuries BC''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1982, p. 284.</ref><ref>A J Toynbee. ''Some Problems of Greek History'', Pp 80; 99-103</ref> The region was annexed to the [[Macedonia (ancient kingdom)|Macedonian kingdom]] during the 4th century BC and became one of its administrative provinces. In medieval times, when the names of [[Lynkestis]] and [[Orestis (region)|Orestis]] had become obsolete, Pelagonia acquired a broader meaning. This is why the [[Battle of Pelagonia]] (1259) between Byzantines and Latins includes also the current [[Kastoria (regional unit)|Kastoria regional unit]] and ancient Orestis.
Strabo calls Pelagonia by the name ''Tripolitis''<ref>Strabo. ''Geographica'', 7.327.</ref> and names only one ancient city of the supposed three in the region; [[Azorus]]. Two notable Pelagonians include the mythological [[Pelagon]], the eponymous of the region, who, according to the [[Greek Mythology]], was son of the river-god [[Axius (mythology)|Axius]] (modern [[Axios]] or Vardar river) and father of the Paeonian [[Asteropaeus]] in [[Homer]]'s ''[[Iliad]]''. The second one is [[Menelaus of Pelagonia]] (ca. 360 BC) who, according to Bosworth, fled his kingdom when it was annexed by [[Philip II of Macedon|Philip II]], finding refuge and citizenship in [[Athens]].<ref>Bosworth, A.B. "Philip II and Upper Macedonia", CQ, 21 (1971).</ref>
Today, Pelagonia is a plain shared between the [[Republic of Macedonia]] and the [[Macedonia (Greece)|region of Macedonia]] in [[Greece]]. It incorporates the southern cities of [[Bitola]] and [[Prilep]] in the Republic of Macedonia and the northwestern city of [[Florina]] in Greece; it is also the location of a key border crossing between the two countries [[Medžitlija-Niki]]. Many [[Helladic period|Mycenaean]] objects have been found in the area, such as the [[double axe]], later found in [[Mycenae]].{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} and are exhibited in the Museum of [[Bitola]].{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}
==See also== *[[List of Ancient Greek tribes]] *[[Pelagonia statistical region]]
