[[Image:Saxon Axis.png|thumb|right|Saxon Axis marked on an 1831 map of Warsaw]]
The '''Saxon Axis''' ({{lang-pl|Oś Saska}}) is a feature of the historical city centre of [[Warsaw]]. It is a line running from the [[Vistula]] through the [[Presidential Palace, Warsaw|Presidential Palace]], the [[Krakowskie Przedmieście]], [[Saxon Square]], [[Saxon Palace]], [[Saxon Garden]], [[Lubomirski Palace, Warsaw|Lubomirski Palace]] to [[Plac Żelaznej Bramy]].<ref> {{cite journal|title=Virtual representation of the historic space riches|last=|first=|doi=10.1016/s0926-5805(03)00049-9|volume=12|journal=Automation in Construction|pages=697–702}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|jstor=887819 : The Burlington Magazine: Vol. 139, No. 1136 (Nov., 1997), pp. 813-815|title=Art under the Polish-Saxon Union. Warsaw and Dresden|author= Katarzyna Murawska-Muthesius}}</ref>
The idea was first proposed by [[August II of Poland]], who intended to build a large Royal palace surrounded by a [[French formal garden|French-style garden]]. The plan was loosely based on the [[baroque]] design of the [[Palace of Versailles]] and was to cover a large part of what is now the city of Warsaw. The main concept, which gave the name to the modern part of the city, assumed the construction of the [[Saxon Palace]], with gardens extending to the both sides along a single axis running exactly through its middle.
Between 1713 and 1726 the king bought 28 parcels of land in the area and invited [[Matthäus Daniel Pöppelmann]] and [[Johann Christoph Naumann]] to design the urban plan. However, financial difficulties made the plan never come true in its entirety. The [[Saxon Garden]] and the [[Saxon Palace]] were constructed, but the planned demolition of the Lubomirski Palace at the [[Plac Żelaznej Bramy]] was called off after August's death in 1733.
During [[World War II]] and the [[Warsaw Uprising]] of 1944, all the buildings along the axis were demolished by the [[Germany|Germans]]. After the war, the Saxon Palace was not rebuilt. However, the garden was refurbished and the demolished [[Lubomirski Palace, Warsaw|Lubomirski Palace]] was rebuilt, but was rotated to fit into the 18th century scheme. In recent times also the [[Warsaw University]] Library at the [[Vistula]] below the river escarpment was added to the list of buildings with main entrances along the axis, and a large golden tablet was placed in the pavement in front of it marking the line running through the city centre.
